E. Modules / build / FFI / LSP specific concerns

E1) Modules will force you to pick: “whole program compile” vs “incremental compilation”

For Go backend, whole-program compile is simplest and still fast enough for most projects.

Future issue: if you aim for incremental later, your internal compiler architecture must be query-based (rust-analyzer style). But you can postpone that.

Fix: adopt a “workspace build” model:
	•	parse all modules
	•	build module graph
	•	typecheck in dependency order (or SCC with recursion if you have it)
	•	then emit one Go package

⸻

E2) FFI requires stable type representations

If you want to call Go:
	•	you need mapping for primitives, records, enums, lists/maps
	•	you need ownership/lifetime rules (esp for strings, slices)
	•	you need error mapping (result ↔ (value, error) or custom struct)

Future issue: if you don’t design FFI types early, you’ll bake in a representation you later regret.

Fix: define an extern system that’s “d.ts-like”:
	•	extern fn net.http.get(url: string) => result[string, http_err]
	•	the compiler generates Go wrapper glue

But you should do this after modules/build so you can import extern decls from packages.

⸻

E3) LSP needs stable spans + project model, not Go FFI

You can do LSP v0 once:
	•	parser is robust
	•	you have spans (byte offsets)
	•	module graph exists

No relation to Go FFI.
